Who'll be the Next Soccer Star?

CMSC320 Data Science Final Project

By: Erin Halper and Maggie Zhou

Introduction

This tutorial focuses on the FIFA 2021 EA Sports video game data. The ultimate goal of the tutorial is to gain a better understanding of the information that differentiates higher ranked players versus lower ranked players. It will analyze the features in the data to better learn about and understand how those features affect a players rank. We want to see how this kind of data can be used to predict the skill of future players and consider how future players would rank based on the features available in this data set. To do this, we will look for existing patterns and trends in the current 2021 data.

Specifically, this data set contains all of male soccer players from the FIFA 2021 video game. The data set has 17981 players (rows) and 9 columns. The columns included in the data that will used in the analysis are name, nationality, position, overall, age, and team. Lets break down what each of these columns mean.

-name - the full name of each player as -first last- (17981 total players in data set)    
-nationality - country the player is from and the international team they play for (162 total nationalities represented in data set)   
-position - position(s) the player plays, separated by by | if they play multiple (15 positions are LW, ST, RWB, LB, CM, LWB, CB, CAM, GK, RW, CDM, RB, LM, RM, CF)     
-overall - rank of the player in the videogame, ranging from 56 to 94 where better players are given higher numbered ranks     
-age - age of the player as of 2021, ranges from 17 to 43     
-team - club team that the player plays for as of 2021 (713 total clubs in data set)

What is overall rank based on? https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/fifa-player-ratings-explained-how-are-the-card-number-stats/1hszd2fgr7wgf1n2b2yjdpgynu

The data set can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/aayushmishra1512/fifa-2021-complete-player-data

These are the Python libraries we will be using to conduct the analysis.

uniqueCountries = set()

for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, "nationality"] not in uniqueCountries:
        uniqueCountries.add(data.at[i, "nationality"])
        countries = countries.append({"country": data.at[i, "nationality"], "lat": "-", "long": "-",

#Calculates average age, average rank, and number of players for each country.

for j in countries.index:
    totalAge = 0
    totalRank = 0
    count = 0
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "nationality"] == countries.at[j, 'country']:
            totalAge += data.at[i, "age"]
            totalRank += data.at[i, "overall"]
            count += 1

    countries.at[j,'avgAge'] = totalAge/count
    countries.at[j,'avgRank'] = totalRank/count
    countries.at[j,'numPlayers'] = count
    
countries

Age and Player Frequency

Let's look at the most common ages in the dataset by comparing age to the age's frequency.

#Age vs. freq
uniqueAges = set()
data

for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, 'age'] not in uniqueAges:
        uniqueAges.add(data.at[i, 'age'])

print(len(uniqueAges))

df3 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["age", "freq"])
for age in uniqueAges:
    count = 0
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, 'age'] == age:
            count += 1
    df3 = df3.append({"age": age, "freq": float(count)}, ignore_index = True)

df3

ax = df3.plot.scatter(x = 'age', y = 'freq')

#Regression for age vs. freq
x = np.linspace(15, 45, num=10)
y =  7.59796313e-01*x**3 + -7.43559176e+01 *x**2 + 2.28659637e+03*x + -2.11636650e+04
obj1 = plt.plot(x, y)
obj2 = plt.scatter(df3['age'], df3['freq'])
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Age vs. Age Frequency Regression in FIFA 2021 Data')
plt.show()


def polyfit(x, y, degree):
    results = {}
    coeffs = np.polyfit(x, y, degree)
    p = np.poly1d(coeffs)
    #calculate r-squared
    yhat = p(x)
    ybar = np.sum(y)/len(y)
    ssreg = np.sum((yhat-ybar)**2)
    sstot = np.sum((y - ybar)**2)
    results['r_squared'] = ssreg / sstot
    
    if degree == 3:
        print("Equation: ", coeffs[0],"x^3 + ", coeffs[1], "x^2 + ", coeffs[2], "x + ", coeffs[3])
        print("R^2:", results['r_squared'])


polyfit(df3['age'], df3['freq'], 3)

Equation:  0.7597963126698706 x^3 +  -74.35591764557223 x^2 +  2286.5963739538265 x +  -21163.665013402748
R^2: 0.9864034598179616

There is clearly a relationship between age and age frequency in the FIFA 2021 data shown in the regression above. If we were interested in seeing whether this pattern generalizes to all FIFA data, the next step would be to perfrom similar analyses on FIFA data from other years including prior as well as future years. If we see similar trends to the pattern here in the other data, then perhaps a generalization could be made about the relationship between age and age frquency in all FIFA data.

#Average age vs. continent
conts = ['Asia', 'Africa', 'South America', 'North America', 'Australia/Oceania', 'Europe']
df2 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["continent", "avgAge"])

for c in conts:
    contPlayerAges = np.array([])
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "continent"] == c:
            contPlayerAges = np.append(contPlayerAges, [data.at[i, "age"] ])

    sum = np.sum(contPlayerAges)
    num = np.size(contPlayerAges)
    meanAge = sum/num


    #np.median(contPlayerAges)
    df2 = df2.append({"continent": c, "avgAge": meanAge}, ignore_index = True)

#Makes bar graph
ax = df2.plot.bar(x='continent', y='avgAge', rot=10)
plt.xlabel('Continent')
plt.ylabel('Average Player Age')
plt.title('Average Player Age for Each Continent')

Age and Nationality

#Creates map to look at relationship between location and average age.

#marker color -> age group (ranges from 17-43)

m = folium.Map(location=[48, -5], zoom_start=2)
for i in countries.index:
    avgAge = countries.at[i, "avgAge"]

    if avgAge >= 17 and avgAge <= 25:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="lightgreen")).add_to(m)

    elif avgAge >= 26 and avgAge <= 34:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="green")).add_to(m)

    if avgAge >= 35 and avgAge <= 43:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = avgAge, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="darkgreen")).add_to(m)
        
m

Looking at the map above, we see that the average age for most countries is around the mid age (26-34) shown in the middle shade of green. Location)

Nationality and Player Frequency

First, let's take a look at the frequency of players in the data from each country (nationality) by looking at them on a map.
The number of players included in the data is separated into 4 color groups on the map below.
The pink markers represent the number of players being between 0 and 373.
The orange markers represent the number of players being between 374 and 747.
The red markers represent the the number of players being between 748 and 1121.
The black markers represent the the number of players being between 1122 and 1496.

If you click on the markers, the number tells the number of players included in the data set for that country.

#Creates map to look at relationship between location and player frequency.

m = folium.Map(location=[48, -5], zoom_start=2)
for i in countries.index:
    freq = countries.at[i, "numPlayers"]

    if freq >= 0 and freq <= 373:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="pink")).add_to(m)

    elif freq >= 374 and freq <= 747:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="orange")).add_to(m)

        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="red")).add_to(m)

    elif freq >= 1122 and freq <= 1496:
        folium.Marker(location=[countries.at[i, "lat"], countries.at[i, "long"]], popup = freq, 
        icon=folium.Icon(color="black")).add_to(m)

In [201]:
uniqueClubs = set()
clubs = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["club", "numPlayers", "avgRank", "avgAge"])
for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, "team"] not in uniqueClubs:
        uniqueClubs.add(data.at[i, "team"])
        clubs = clubs.append({"club": data.at[i, "team"], "numPlayers": "-", "avgRank": "-",
                "avgAge": "-"}, ignore_index = True)


print("Number of clubs in data set:", len(uniqueClubs))
#Takes a while to run - about 3 min
for j in clubs.index:
    numPlayers = 0
    rankTotal = 0
    ageTotal = 0
    for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "team"] == clubs.at[j, "club"]:
            numPlayers += 1
            rankTotal += data.at[i, "overall"]
            ageTotal += data.at[i, "age"]
    avgRank = rankTotal / numPlayers
    avgAge = ageTotal / numPlayers
    clubs.at[j, "numPlayers"] = numPlayers
    clubs.at[j, "avgRank"] = avgRank 
    clubs.at[j, "avgAge"] = avgAge

Some players play more than one position. To account for that, we will make additional columns for each additional position that the player plays.

In [203]:
#organizing data based on position
d2 = data.filter(["name", "age", 'overall', "position", "nationality"])
d3 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["name", "age", "rank", "position", "nationality"])

# reformat position coloumn to account for multiple positions played by one player by adding a new row per position in df3
for i, row in d2.iterrows():
    pos = d2.at[i, "position"]
    positions = pos.split('|')
    for pos in positions:
        newRow = {'name': d2.at[i, 'name'],'age': d2.at[i, "age"], 'rank': d2.at[i, "overall"], 'position': pos, 'nationality': d2.at[i, "nationality"]}
        d3 = d3.append(newRow, ignore_index = True)

countries['mostFreqPos'] = '-'
defense = set(['CB', 'GK', 'RB', 'LB', 'LWB', 'RWB'])
midfield = set(['RM', 'LM', 'CAM', 'CM', 'CDM'])
attack = set(['ST', 'CF', 'LW', 'RW'])
for i in countries.index:
    dc = 0
    mc = 0
    ac = 0
    maxPos = ""
    for j in d3.index:
        if d3.at[j, "nationality"] == countries.at[i, "country"]:
            if d3.at[j, "position"] in defense:
                dc += 1
            elif d3.at[j, "position"] in midfield:
                mc += 1
            elif d3.at[j, "position"] in attack:
                ac += 1

    max = np.max(([dc, mc, ac]))
    if max == dc:
        maxPos = "defense"
    elif max == mc:
        maxPos = "midfield"
    elif max == ac:
        maxPos = "attack"
    countries.at[i, "mostFreqPos"] = maxPos

Average Rank and Age

Now, let's take a look at the relationship between average age and rank.

In [212]:
#finds average rank for each age
uniqueAges = set()
for i in data.index:
        if data.at[i, "age"] not in uniqueAges: 
            uniqueAges.add(data.at[i, "age"])

print(len(uniqueAges))

allAgePlayerRanks = {}
ageAvgRank = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["age", "avgRank"])

for a in uniqueAges:
    AgePlayerRanks = np.array([])
    for i in data.index:
            if data.at[i, "age"] == a:
                AgePlayerRanks = np.append(AgePlayerRanks, [ data.at[i, "overall"] ])

    sum = np.sum(AgePlayerRanks)
    num = np.size(AgePlayerRanks)
    
    meanRanking = sum/num
    n = {a: meanRanking}
    allAgePlayerRanks.update(n)
    ageAvgRank = ageAvgRank.append({"age": float(a), "avgRank": meanRanking}, ignore_index = True)

ageAvgRank
ax = ageAvgRank.plot.scatter(x = 'age', y = 'avgRank')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Average Rank')
plt.title('Average Player Rank for Each Age in FIFA 2021 Data')
plt.show()

27

In the graph above, we see that the relationship between age and average rank for each age in the FIFA 2021 data set follows a parabola shape. That is, the middle ages tend to have the highest average ranks and the much younger/older ages have lower ranks. This makes sense as some of the players we think about when talking about the best soccer players fall around the middle ages such as Lionel Messi (34) and Cristiano Ronaldo (36). Why might this be the case? This may be related to these players have sufficient experience (compared to younger players), and they also carry youth and are able to be physically fit to perform well (compared to older players). Thus, the middle-aged players are able maintain a strong balance of experience and fitness. ----

The main marker color represents the player's ranking. The darker blue represents the highest ranked players (rank 90 to 94), and the ligher blue represents the lower ranked (out of the top 100, so still high!) players (rank 85 to 89).
The icon color represents the player's age. The lighter green represents the younger players (aged 17 to 25), the middle green shade represents the mid-older players (aged 26 to 34), and the darker green represents the oldest players (aged 35 to 43).

It is important to note and keep in mind the frquency of players in each continent (from above) as well because continents with a small amount of players may only have higher ranked players representing the country. Whereas, continents will a high amount of players in the data may have a larger variety and broader range of ranked players (Europe). This wider range would heavily impact the mean. The presence of any outliers would have an effect on the mean and may bring it down a bit. Whereas, continents will only higher ranked players may not have these low outliers or at least as many low outliers to bring the mean down.

Hypothesis Testing

1) Two Sample Z-Test for Mean

Hypothesis testing for difference between two population means.
Population 1 will be all of the players who are between ages 26-34 (middle ages in the data) and Population 2 will be players who are between ages 17-25 and 35-43 (the rest of the players in the data set, youngest and oldest). We will be testing to see whether the true average rank of players between ages 27-35 is higher than that of the rest of the players at .01 significance level.

First, we will need to organize our data into their correct population based on the age.

In [218]:
pop1 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["player", "age", "overall"])
pop2 = pandas.DataFrame(columns = ["player", "age", "overall"])
for i in data.index:
    if data.at[i, "age"] >= 26 and data.at[i, "age"] <= 34:
        pop1 = pop1.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "age": data.at[i, "age"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"]}, ignore_index = True)
    else:
        pop2 = pop2.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "age": data.at[i, "age"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"]}, ignore_index = True)

Two Sample Z-Test Hypothesis Testing for Mean at .01 significance level

Null Hypothesis: mu1 - mu2 = 0
Alternate Hypothesis: mu1 - mu2 > 0
where mu1 is the true average rank of players aged 26-34 in FIFA 21 and mu2 is the true average rank of players aged 17-25, 35-43 un FIFA 21.

Assume Null Hypothesis is true.

In [221]:
alpha = .01

testStatistic = (avg1 - avg2 - 0) / (np.sqrt( ((sd1**2)/m) + ((sd2**2)/n) ) )
print("Test Statistic =", testStatistic)

#P(Z > testStatistic)
pValue = 1 - (st.norm.cdf(testStatistic))
print("P-value =", pValue)

if pValue <= alpha:
    print("Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.")
else:
    print("Do not reject null hypothesis.")

Test Statistic = 40.67337137934258
P-value = 0.0
Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

As per above, p-value = 0 and alpha = .01.
As p-value <= alpha, we will reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

Based on the sample data, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the true average rank of players aged 26-34 in FIFA 21 is higher than the true average rank of the rest of the players (players aged 17-25, 35-43) in FIFA 21 at .01 significance level.

2) Two Sample Z-Test for Proportion

Hypothesis testing for difference between two population proportions.
Population 1 will be the top 2000 ranked players in the FIFA 21 data set and Population 2 will be the rest of the players, so the bottom 12981 ranked players in the FIFA 21 data set. We will be testing to see whether the true proportion of players with a European nationality is higher amongst the top 2000 ranked players than the rest of the players at .01 significance level.

First, we will need to organize our data into their correct population based on the rank.

In [222]:

    pop1 = pop1.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"], "continent": data.at[i, "continent"]}, ignore_index = True)

for i in data.tail(16981).index:
    pop2 = pop2.append({"player": data.at[i, "name"], "overall": data.at[i, "overall"], "continent": data.at[i, "continent"]}, ignore_index = True)

Two Sample Z-Test Hypothesis Testing for Proportion at .01 significance level

Null Hypothesis: p1 - p2 = 0
Alternate Hypothesis: p1 - p2 > 0
where p1 is the true proportion of players with European nationality in top 2000 ranked players in FIFA 21 and p2 is the true proportion of players with European nationality in the rest of the players (bottom 16981 ranked players in FIFA 21).

Assume Null Hypothesis is true.
We must check conditions for performing the hypothesis test. We will be ensuring the following conditions hold first.
mp1 >= 10 -> 2000(.6205) = 1241
mq1 >= 10 -> 2000(.3795) = 759
np2 >= 10 -> 16981(.5655) = 9602.7555
nq2 >= 10 -> 16981(.4345) = 7378.2445

In [225]:
alpha = .01

pHat = ((m/(m+n))*p1) + ((n/(m+n))*p2)
qHat = 1 - pHat

testStatistic = (p1 - p2 - 0) / ( np.sqrt(pHat*qHat*((1/m)+(1/n))) )

print("Test Statistic =", testStatistic)

#P(Z > testStatistic)
pValue = 1 - (st.norm.cdf(testStatistic))
print("P-value =", pValue)

if pValue <= alpha:
    print("Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.")
else:
    print("Do not reject null hypothesis.")

Test Statistic = 4.69978771444471
P-value = 1.302160350546977e-06
Reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

As per above, p-value = 0 and alpha = .01. As p-value <= alpha, we will reject null hypothesis in favor of alternate hypothesis.

Based on the sample data, there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the true proportion of players with a European nationality is higher amongst the top 2000 ranked players than the rest of the players at .01 significance level.

#Quadratic Regression
def polyfit(x, y, degree):
    results = {}
    coeffs = np.polyfit(x, y, degree)
    p = np.poly1d(coeffs)
    #calculate r-squared
    yhat = p(x)
    ybar = np.sum(y)/len(y)
    ssreg = np.sum((yhat-ybar)**2)
    sstot = np.sum((y - ybar)**2)
    results['r_squared'] = ssreg / sstot
    print("Equation: ", coeffs[0],"x^2 + ", coeffs[1], "x + ", coeffs[2])
    print("R^2:", results['r_squared'])

polyfit(ageAvgRank['age'], ageAvgRank['avgRank'], 2)

Ideas for More Analysis

-It would not only be interesting, but it would be important to compare the findings from FIFA's 2021 data to their data from previous (and future) years. For a few of the numeric relationships, we performed regressions on the patterns, so it would be important to run similar regressions on previous and future data to see if those trends and regressions can be generalized to most FIFA data or whether the patterns found from this analysis was unique and specific to this year's data.  
-On the same note, it would be interesting to see how any of the trends we found change throughout the years and analyze the patterns over time.     
-Once we have analyzed the data from several years, it would be important to look for any of the same trends. If there are consistent patterns corresponding to rank throughout the years, then it would be interesting to make a predictive rank model with those features that have consistent data.    
-Another idea that could be tested is the effect of having a few to many highly ranked players on a team and compare that to performance (both on club teams as well as international teams). The obvious hypothesis would be that teams with many highly ranked players would yield better team performance. However, this may not always be the case. For example, having too many highly ranked players that do not compliment each other may lead to conflicting styles and may not have the compounding effect that would be inferred.      
-Once data from past years have been analyzed, it would also be interesting to look at the results of tournament data and compare how the tournament data results compare to the analysis findings for the corresponding year. This could be conducted for both international tournamnets and club tournaments. For example, international tournaments include the World Cup, Euro Cup, the Olympics, Copa America, etc. Club tournaments include the UEFA Cup and results from the UEFA Champions League.       
-It would also be interesting to look at the effect of players switching club teams by seeing whether there are drastic changes in the performance of the club that they switched to/from. This would have to look at data from prior and future years in order to observe changes in the player's club team.

Links to FIFA data sets from other years: https://www.kaggle.com/search?q=fifa+player+dataset

Insights

For the FIFA 2021 data, we found the following key findings:

-Age and player rank have a parabolic relationship. That is, the middle ages of the ages represented in the data set, had the higher player ranks. The more younger and older rages in the data set had lower ranks. We saw this trend visually with a regression and also performed a two sample hypothesis test that supported these results. It found that ages 27-35 had a higher mean player rank than the rest of the players with ages 17-25, 35-43.  
-Most of the top ranked players have European nationality. There is a larger proportion of players that are from European countries in the top 2000 ranked players than in the rest of the players in the data set. This was found using a two sample hypothesis test. While performing the test, it was found that over half of the top 2000 ranked players are from Europe.   
-All of the club teams with the highest average player rankings are located in Europe. 
-Europe was by far the most frequent player nationality in the data.   
-The most common player ages represented in the data set were around ages 22-28. The ages became less common for much younger and much older ages (following a bell-curve).
-The center back and center midfield were the positions that the most players were listed as playing.
-The average ages for the three groups of positions (defense, midfiled, and forward) were all very similar (around 25-27) with defense being slightly older, followed by forward, and then midfield.

Conclusion

We now have a much better understanding of the information contained in the FIFA 2021 data set! We have comprehensively explored the various features of the data set including age, nationality (country and continent), club team, and position. We looked at the distribution of these features in the data set and the connections between these different features. In order to make stronger observations and to give statements regarding the patterns about FIFA data in general (not just from 2021), it will be necessary to analyze the FIFA data from prior years to see if the patterns we currently see can be generalized from finding similar trends those years as well. We will have to see if the insights above can be generalized from past data. If we do see similar trends over time, then the next step will focus on using it to predict the rankings for future players.
